				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi =45^{\circ }$$\end{document}, both visible and near-infrared resonances are excited, resulting in a coupling of the NIR and visible modes, as illustrated in the field enhancement spectrum in Fig. 2g and field distributions in Fig. 2h,i, respectively for illumination frequencies of 246.1 and 420.6 THz. Thus, by adjusting the polarization, we switch the character of the plasmonic mode from dark to bright. By sweeping the polarization angle \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
